article.linkText: Lakers beat Nets in battle of short-handeds
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Shaquille O'Neal made the New Jersey Nets pay for Hack-a-Shaq. The Lakers center, who scored 40 points and had 12 rebounds, made six free throws in the final 3:44 Tuesday night as Los Angeles held off the Nets 101-92 and won their second straight without Kobe Bryant. The sellout crowd of 18,997 began chanting "MVP! MVP!" when O'Neal stepped to the line -- expressing their choice over Nets' MVP contender Jason Kidd. O'Neal, who was just 2-of-10 from the line earlier in the game, was accurate enough late, going 6-for-10 to keep New Jersey at bay. "Shaq made free throws in the fourth quarter," New Jersey coach Byron Scott said. "I said, `I'm going to send him to the line and see if he could make them.' "He was making them and looking at me and winking. He was having fun out there, and I was enjoying it." Kidd, who had 19 points, 10 assists and eight rebounds, thought O'Neal was having a good time, too. "I know he enjoys that (making free throws) coming down the stretch. He's improved his free throw shooting, so it wasn't so much Hack-a-Shaq, but we didn't have too many other choices," Kidd said. O'Neal, on the eve of his 30th birthday, was pleased with his free throw delivery, if not satisfied with the 8-of-20 total. "Even though I missed a lot of them, all of them were right there," O'Neal said. "They were just popping in and out." Kidd was gracious about the MVP chants for O'Neal, saying, "He's well-deserving. I mean, he's the `Big Daddy,' or whatever those names are that he has. He's one of the most dominant players on this planet. So, for them to be chanting that, that's their opinion." Both the Lakers, who moved into a tie with Sacramento for the NBA's best record, and the Nets, with the Eastern Conference's best mark, were missing key players. Bryant completed his two-game suspension for fighting. The Nets were without Kenyon Martin, suspended for one game for drawing his sixth flagrant foul of the season, and regular center Todd MacCulloch, out with a sore left foot. The Lakers (42-17) led by as much as 64-46 midway through the third quarter. But Kidd and Lucious Harris led a 17-6 run to close out the period and trim Los Angeles' lead to 70-63. New Jersey overtook the Lakers in the fourth quarter and was up 79-78 with 5:58 left. But Los Angeles scored the next nine points, then went up 91-82 on Derek Fisher's 3-pointer with 3:17 remaining. The closest New Jersey got afterward was 95-92 with 1:40 left. O'Neal then made three of four free throws and Derek Fisher and Robert Horry added two each. Fisher had 16 points Horry had 12 points and 13 rebounds. The Nets had six players score in double figures. Keith Van Horn had 13 points and 14 rebounds, Harris had 17 points and rookie Richard Jefferson, starting in Martin's spot, scored 15. Without New Jersey's 7-foot, 280-pound MacCulloch going against him, the 7-1, 335-pound O'Neal dominated the middle against rookie Jason Collins, a 7-footer who weighs 260, and Aaron Williams, 6-9 and 225. O'Neal center was 16-of-21 from the floor. Los Angeles outscored New Jersey (39-20) 15-5 to start the third quarter, taking a 64-46 advantage before the Nets began chipping away at the lead. O'Neal had 24 points by halftime. Van Horn had 11 first-half points for the Nets, who shot just 34 percent from the floor in the half to 52 percent by the Lakers. The Lakers finished at 48 percent, the Nets at 35 percent. Bryant and Indiana's Reggie Miller each were suspended for two games for fighting on the court just after the Lakers' win over the Pacers on Friday night. Los Angeles defeated Houston on Sunday after Bryant's suspension was announced. The Lakers also picked up two games on Sacramento in the best-record race during Bryant's absence, as the Kings lost to Indiana -- without Miller -- and Portland.

Game notes
The game against the Lakers was the first of four on the road for the Nets in five nights. They're at Phoenix on Wednesday. ... Los Angeles F Samaki Walker, on the injured list with a sore right elbow, isn't scheduled to make the trip to Utah for Thursday's game against the Jazz. With a three-day break for the Lakers before their next game, Walker is expected to play against the New York Knicks in Los Angeles on Sunday.
